                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d645">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 322.93/3.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Chargé d’Affaires</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 40.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 30, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department is in receipt of your despatch No.
                    66 of the 2d instant, transmitting copies [etc.].</p>
                <p>The action of the Legation as reported in your despatch has the approval of the
                    Department. You may, however, with the acquiescence of the Ecuadorian
                    Government, informally submit to the Minister for Foreign Affairs a list of such
                    claims for consideration by that Government.</p>
                <p>Under no circumstances should formal representations in this matter be made by
                    the Legation, unless in accordance with express instructions from the
                    Department.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
